# Thoughts on Aramaic Primacy

## Introduction

Let me start with a definition. Unless otherwise noted, I use the term Aramaic Primacy (or AP) to refer to the claim that ***the entire New Testament*** was originally written in Aramaic as represented by the Peshitta. This is the claim made by a former Catholicos Patriarch of the Assyrian Church of the East, Mar Eshai Shimun XXIII (although the current Patriarch has refused to repeat the claim), and it is also made by Bauscher, Lamsa and others.

On pages 4 through 13 of The Aramaic New Testament (*The 1st Century Aramaic Bible in Plain English – The New Testament with Psalms & Proverbs*, translation by Pastor Glenn David Bauscher), is an introduction written by Bauscher. Of that section, pages 4 through 7 contain Bauscher’s arguments in favor of AP, and the remainder has information about his philosophy of translation as well as experiences and thoughts about the translation itself.

What I will focus on in this paper is a review of the arguments in favor of AP. Of particular importance here is that in all of my reading of other sources who advocate in favor of AP, I have found that Bauscher’s introduction includes all of the most important pro-AP arguments. For this reason, my focus will be on Bauscher’s claims in pages 4 through 7 of his translation\.

## Fundamental Aramaic Primacy Claims

While reading through the introduction to Bauscher’s NT, and other sources, I cataloged each of the claims made and categorized them into three broad areas. The three categories and their sub-claims are listed below. For this paper, I will discuss each of the categories broadly, and where necessary, comment on the individual claims.

### **Category: The linguistic landscape of Palestine and the language(s) spoken by the Jews**

* During the 70-year Babylonian captivity, the Jews adopted the Aramaic language over the Hebrew language

* The Hebrew language became a dead language by the time the 70-year captivity was concluded

* Following the Babylonian captivity and up to the time of Christ the Jews used Aramaic exclusively

* During and after the time of Christ, Aramaic was the exclusive language of the majority of the common people of Palestine

* The Jewish diaspora in Greek-speaking areas maintained their use of Aramaic, even after several hundred years

* The priests forbade the use of Greek in the Temple

### **Category: The language(s) spoken by Jesus, the disciples, NT authors and original audience**

* Jesus, the disciples and all authors of the NT spoke Aramaic, not Greek as their first language

* If Jesus, the disciples and NT authors knew any Greek, they knew it only poorly, certainly not well enough to write the original NT texts using Greek

* The audiences of the NT authors were all Aramaic speakers, including the audiences of the Pauline epistles

### **Category: Details about the Aramaic Language and Peshitta text**

* Peshitta is written in 1st\-Century Palestinian Aramaic

* Peshitta is unchanged from the first editions

* There are numerous clues in the Aramaic and Greek texts of the NT to indicate that the Aramaic text, specifically the Peshitta, is the original text of the NT

## The linguistic landscape of Palestine and the language(s) spoken by the Jews

The first thing that I would like to state here is that everything (or almost everything) that you think that you know about the Hebrew language post-Babylonian exile is false.

Up until the 1950s, the general consensus regarding the Hebrew language was that it had died out as a spoken language during the Babylonian exile, and that following the return from Babylon, the Jews had switched entirely to Aramaic as the language of everyday use among the people, with Hebrew only being used as a liturgical language.

This view is expressed in the 1958 edition of *The Oxford Dictionary of the Christian Church*, which, under the “Hebrew” article, says that Hebrew “ceased to be a spoken language around the fourth century BCE”.

However, if we fast-forward to the 1997 edition, the same article changed dramatically, stating that Hebrew “continued to be used as a spoken and written language in the New Testament period.”

In fact, researchers are now saying that Hebrew continued as a living language until sometime between 200AD and 400AD.

So, what happened that caused such a dramatic shift in scholarly views?

Two things happened: one is that historical linguists made a detailed review of a significant number of ancient documents which had been discovered, and their conclusions entirely invalidated the previous consensus view. The second thing that happened was the discovery of the Qumran scrolls. These scrolls include information that tells us that not only was Aramaic not the sole language of Palestine, it wasn’t even the majority language. This information coincided with the other ancient documentation that was coming to light, and together they revealed quite a startling picture:

* In Galilee, about half of the population spoke Greek as their first language, about 30% spoke Hebrew as their first language and the rest spoke Aramaic as a first language. Consider that Matthew refers to “Galilee of the Gentiles” (Matt 4:15). Nazareth, where Jesus grew up, was only four miles from Sepphoris, the largest city in Galilee – and Sepphoris is known to have been a predominantly Greek city, founded by Greeks, and where the Greek language and culture were predominant.

* In Samaria, as a first language, the majority spoke Hebrew, with Greek and Aramaic being minority languages. Remember that the Samaritans spoke Hebrew, but never went to the Babylonian captivity and were still using Hebrew when the Judeans returned from Babylon.

* And in Judea, the split between the three languages was about equal. In fact, Greek was so commonly spoken, that there were even Greek-speaking synagogues in Jerusalem for the Hellenized Jews (as attested by the Theodoton Inscription, and in Acts chapter 6). In the Aramaic synagogues, the Torah readings were translated into the Targums which were later compiled into what became the Aramaic Old Testament; while in the Greek synagogues, the Torah readings were repeated in Greek using the Septuagint texts. Among 

And in all three areas, regardless of what their first language was, the majority of Jews were familiar with all three languages. Greek was the language of government and trade, Aramaic was the language of contracts, and Hebrew was used for prayers and liturgy. Anything else was according to the preferences of the speakers and listeners.

During Greek rule (between the return from Babylon and the Roman period), one of the Greek kings, so fed up with the rebellious nationalism from the Jews, passed a law forbidding the use of Hebrew – requiring Aramaic instead. Obviously his law had little effect, but it is clear historical evidence that Hebrew had not died out in Babylon.

In fact, at this point, there is only one source of information from the 1st Century which tells us that 1st Century Palestine was monolingual: Josephus. And it turns out that even Josephus didn’t really claim that the Jews were monolingual. He is misquoted as saying so, when what he really said was the opposite: most Jews spoke many languages and it was only the leadership of the Jews who spoke only one language because they spent so much of their time studying the Law and the Interpretation of the Law that they didn’t have time for anything else. I find it very curious that Bauscher would base his entire theory on a misquote.

By now, only the last two points of the linguistic landscape category have not been covered, so I will address them individually.

Regarding the use of Aramaic by the Jewish Diaspora in Greek lands, Bauscher’s claim is suspect. In fact, I find it illogical that Bauscher would argue that the Jews had so quickly abandoned Hebrew – *Lashon HaQodesh*, the Holy Language – after only 70 years in Babylon, but would then desperately cling to Aramaic – a language that Mishnah calls “evil” and the priests considered “the devil’s own language” – for several hundred years while living among the Greeks.

We know from archaeology and from historical records that the Jewish Diaspora used Hebrew as their liturgical language. We also know from archaeology as well as from the Bible itself that wherever they lived, the Jews adopted the local language of whatever region they lived in for everyday use: see Acts 2:1-11.

So if the Jews maintained the use of Hebrew, especially for liturgical purposes, and considered Aramaic “evil”, then why would they require the use of Aramaic in the Temple, as Bauscher claims? Well, actually Bauscher says that the Jews forbade the use of Greek in the Temple, which while not technically false, is actually a half-truth. The full truth is that the Jews forbade the use of ***every language except Hebrew***. In other words, ***the use of Aramaic in the Temple was also forbidden***. Curious that Bauscher just happens to neglect to mention this tiny little detail. Bauscher is starting to sound more and more like Evolutionists and Global Warming proponents – he uses a lot of what, at first, appear to be reasonable arguments, but when you start digging, the real picture is vastly different.

# The language(s) spoken by Jesus, the disciples, NT authors and original audience

What language(s) did Jesus speak? We know from direct quotations in the NT that Jesus spoke Aramaic. Given that the priests required the use of Hebrew in the Temple, and given that Jesus is shown in several situations where he would have to have used Hebrew (when he was 12, he spent several days in the Temple arguing with the priests, and while travelling through Hebrew-speaking Samaria he stopped and talked with the woman by the well), it is a virtual certainty that Jesus also knew Hebrew.

But what about Jesus speaking Greek? Again, there is evidence to support this: Jesus grew up in “Galilee of the Gentiles” where 50% of the population spoke Greek as their first language, and almost everyone knew Greek well enough to converse. Jesus is also shown several times in the Gospels speaking with individuals who most likely knew little or no Aramaic or Hebrew (Matt 8:5-13; Mark 7:24-30; John 18:28-38). Based on this evidence, it is not a matter of “if” Jesus spoke Greek, but how much and how often he spoke it.

One researcher put it this way: “the evidence regarding what is known about the use of Greek in ancient Palestine, including the cosmopolitan Hellenistic character of lower Galilee, the epigraphic and literary evidence, including coins, papyri, literary writers, inscriptions and funerary texts, but most of all several significant contexts in the Gospels, all points in one direction: whereas it is not always known how much and on which occasions Jesus spoke Greek, it is virtually certain that he used Greek at various times in his itinerant ministry.” (Porter, Stanley E. “Did Jesus Ever Teach in Greek?” Tyndale Bulletin, 44 1993 p.235).

Consider these quotes: “Hellenistic culture, which implied the use of Greek, dominated every aspect of life and society \[in Galilee\]” (J.N. Sevenster Do You Know Greek? How much Greek could the first Jewish Christian have known? Translated by J. de Bruin; Leiden, Netherlands: E. J. Brill, 1968, p96). “It is not legitimate to think of Jesus as growing up in linguistic and cultural isolation. Nazareth was situated along a branch of and had a position overlooking one of the busiest trade routes in ancient Palestine, the Via Maris, which reached from Damascus to the Mediterranean” (Stanley E. Porter, “Did Jesus Ever Teach in Greek?”, p.211). “This means that for Jesus to have conversed with inhabitants of cities in the Galilee, and especially the cities of the Decapolis and the Phoenician region, he would have had to have known Greek, certainly at the conversational level” (H.C. Kee, “Early Christianity in the Galilee: Reassessing the Evidence from the Gospels”, in Levine (ed.), Galilee in Late Antiquity, 21).

The fact that John 21:15-17 shows Jesus making a word play of three separate pairs of Greek words (word plays which are lost in Aramaic) is strong evidence that the original conversation had to have been in Greek.

Regarding the widespread use of Greek in Judea, consider also the fact that of the tombstones and sepulchral inscriptions in Jerusalem, dating from the time of Christ, more are inscribed in Greek than any other language. Even many inscriptions in the burial chamber of what is believed to be the family of Caiaphas the High Priest are written in Greek. This indicates that Greek had to have been used even by the priests.

Acts 9:29 talks about Paul debating with Greek-speaking Jews in Jerusalem.

Regarding the disciples, they were also from Galilee and Judea, and would have had just as broad an exposure to the Greek language as Jesus. In fact, while evidence in the NT points to the likelihood that Jesus spoke Aramaic as his first language, there is no such information to make a similar claim about the disciples and other NT authors. Since many of the disciples were from “Galilee of the Gentiles”, it more than probable that several (if not all) of them spoke Greek as a first language.

About other people mentioned in the NT who were not disciples, Colossians 4:10-14 contains some interesting information. In it, three individuals (Aristarchus, Mark and Jesus/Justus) send their greetings. These three are mentioned in verse 11 as being the only ones working with Paul who are “of the circumcision,” or as some translations put it, “Jews.” Following this, there are three other individuals mentioned as also working with Paul and sending their greetings – one of these three who is not “of the circumcision” is none other than “Luke, the doctor”, the author of the Gospel of Luke and the Acts of the Apostles.

Paul is also mentioned in the book of Acts as talking to a group of people in a Greek-speaking area, then switching to Hebrew (not Aramaic – even the Peshitta text uses the term for the Hebrew language, not the Aramaic language). But if Paul switched to Hebrew from another language, what was that other language? The Bible doesn’t say, but it’s obvious from his audience that he had to have been speaking Greek. Paul is also mentioned as going to Athens and preaching directly to the most learned of the Greeks in their aeropagus (Acts 17:18-34). How could he discuss the Gospel so elegantly with them if he didn’t know Greek intimately?

Regarding Bauscher’s claim that the audiences of the NT authors (including the audiences of the Pauline epistles) were all Aramaic speakers, the text of the NT shows this claim to be false. Both the Gospel of Luke and the Acts of the Apostles are addressed to “Theophilus”. Theophilus is a Greek word meaning “Friend of God”. While it is unclear if “Theophilus” is an actual person with that name, or if it is a general reference to all believers, it is clearly addressed to a Greek audience – either to a Greek-speaking individual named Theophilus, or to people who understand the Greek “friend of God” reference. What is more important here is that in the Aramaic texts, the name shows up as a transliteration of the Greek word “Theophilus” and not as an Aramaic equivalent, evidence pointing to a Greek origin.

Furthermore, Bauscher makes a particular point in his argument by saying that the Pauline epistles written to Christians living in cities like Rome, Corinth, etc., were primarily directed towards the Jewish converts, and not to Greeks. The problems with this argument are that, (1) as stated above, the Jews in Greek-speaking areas had not maintained Aramaic, (2) the language that they did keep alive in their synagogues was Hebrew, and (3) Paul calls himself the “apostle to the Gentiles” (Gal 2:7, 8), so it is highly illogical to claim that the apostle to the Gentiles would have written his epistles exclusively to the former Jews of those cities, instead of being written to both Jews and Gentiles alike. Since they were written to all believers, they would have to have been written in Greek so all believers in those cities could read them. And even if they had been written exclusively to the Jews, they would have been written in Hebrew, not Aramaic.

# Details about the Aramaic Language and Peshitta text

One of the important aspects of the Roman empire during the time of Christ, especially around the eastern Mediterranean, is the fact that there was one standard Greek dialect, called Koine Greek. This widespread use of a stable language, coupled with the “relatively” stable *Pax Romana*, allowed the new Christian faith to spread very widely within a short period of time. Having the scriptures in that language easily contributed to this spread.

If there was one, standard Aramaic dialect that was widely recognized throughout a large geographic area, having the scriptures in this language could also contribute to rapid growth of the Christian faith. However, historical linguists tell us a different story. Thus, any Aramaic text would only have been accessible to the people living near where it was produced.

It is true that the strong power of the Babylonian and Medo-Persian empires allowed them to maintain one standard Aramaic dialect for as long as they existed. However, within a short time after the Greeks conquered the Persian empire, since there was no longer any glue to hold the Aramaic language together. It fractured into numerous localized dialects which, with time and distance, became more and more mutually unintelligible.

According to historical linguists, by the time of Christ there was a recognizable difference between Judean, Samaritan and Galilean Aramaic dialects, which along with Damascene Aramaic and Aleppan Aramaic are broadly classified as Old Western Aramaic. The dialects to the North and East of Palestine and stretching from Syria into Mesopotamia and Persia are classified as Old Eastern Aramaic, and include what is now referred to as Syriac – this dialect was the official language of the kingdom of Osroene which was centered around the city of Edessa. Note that the dialects of Palestine are classified as Western Aramaic, while Syriac is classified as Eastern Aramaic, indicating Syriac is more similar to the Aramaic of Mesopotamia and Persia than to the Palestinian dialects.

The very fact that Peshitta is written in Syriac indicates that it is not the Aramaic dialect spoken by Jesus and the disciples.

Around the third century, there was a major language shift for both Eastern and Western Aramaic. The Western Aramaic dialects were mostly subsumed into Middle Galilean Aramaic which became the dominant dialect and is the language in which the Talmud is written. The eastern dialects continued to split – Syriac becoming mutually unintelligible with the other dialects to the east as well as further out of sync with the Western Aramaic languages to the south. Middle Syriac experienced its golden age during the 4th through 6th centuries with a large output of liturgical literature.

Again, note that the Talmud was written in Middle Galilean Aramaic, a different dialect from Peshitta, but still closer linguistically to the 1st Century Galilean Aramaic that would have been spoken by Jesus and the disciples.

Historical linguists can look at the grammar, syntax and vocabulary of a given Aramaic text and identify not only the region where it was produced, but the time period as well. And their analysis of the Peshitta is that it is written in the Edessan dialect of Middle Syriac which was in common use during the above-mentioned 4th through 6th century golden age.

For a demonstration on how the two dialects are different, let’s look at how to express “he will X” in verbs. This is the 3rd person singular masculine imperfective form. Let’s use this form with the verb *k-t-b*, meaning “to write”. In first century Galilean Aramaic, this would be *yiktob*. And in fifth century Edessan Syriac, this would be *nektub*. Which of these two forms appears in Peshitta? The second. Exclusively. In other words, the 3rd Masculine Impefective form is created in 5th Century Edessan Syriac by the use of the prefix *ne-* which would have been *yi-* in 1st Century Galilean Aramaic. Here are three texts that I easily found that use the *ne-* form for the 3rd Masculine Impefective form of the verb: Matt 4:6 (***ne**paqqed*), Matt 12:19 (***ne**thare*), Mark 13:27 (***ne**shaddar*).

An important note regarding the ***ne-*** prefix for this verb form is that of all historical dialects of Aramaic, this form only existed in Edessan Syriac starting around the 3rd Century. This fact alone proves that Peshitta (which uses this prefix exclusively) could not possibly have been the original text of the New Testament.

It is worth pointing out the Peshitta reading of Mark 15:34 in which ***two different Aramaic dialects*** are used: “And in the ninth hour Yeshua cried out in a loud voice, and he said: ‘Eil, Eil, lemana Shabaqthani’, which is, ‘My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?’” Why the need to translate an Aramaic phrase into Aramaic? Because the quote (Jesus actual words) is in 1st\-Century Palestinian Aramaic and the translation is in 5th\-Century Edessan Syriac – the same dialect that is used in the rest of Peshitta.

Given this, it can be said with absolute certainty that ***if*** the New Testament had originally been written in Aramaic, the Peshitta ***absolutely does not*** represent the original text. This is a plain contradiction of numerous AP proponents, including Bauscher, who include this quote: “With reference to....the originality of the Peshitta text, as the Patriarch and Head of the Holy Apostolic and Catholic Church of the East, we wish to state, that the Church of the East received the scriptures from the hands of the blessed Apostles themselves in the Aramaic original, the language spoken by our Lord Jesus Christ Himself, and that the Peshitta is the text of the Church of the East which has come down from the Biblical times ***without any change or revision***” (emphasis supplied). Since the Aramaic dialect of Peshitta is of a different region than that spoken by Jesus and the disciples, and was not spoken during Bible times, this statement cannot be true. Let me repeat: The text of Peshitta is absolutely not the original text of the New Testament \- wrong place and wrong time.

For more details about why Peshitta cannot be the original text of the New Testament, see this page: [http://aramaicnt.org/articles/problems-with-peshitta-primacy/](http://aramaicnt.org/articles/problems-with-peshitta-primacy/), which was written by a professional Aramaic translator who specializes in First Century Galilean Aramaic.

Further evidence shows that the Church of the East did not initially accept the books of 2 Peter, 2 John, 3 John, Jude, Revelation as canon. This is evidenced by the earliest Peshitta manuscripts not containing these five books. If Peshitta did not contain them, then where did their Aramaic texts come from? History tells us that the Byzantine churches put pressure on the Eastern churches to include them, so some time around the 6th to 7th centuries, they were translated into Aramaic from Greek and added to subsequent Peshitta manuscripts. Thus, we absolutely know from history that these five books in Peshitta are Greek translations and anyone who tries to claim otherwise is either lying or grossly misinformed.

Another point that the AP camp fails to admit is that there are Aramaic texts older than Peshitta which use a different dialect than that of Peshitta. In particular, the Syriac Sinaiticus and Curetonian Gospels manuscripts are known to be older than the earliest Peshitta manuscripts, yet they each use different Aramaic dialects and are very different from Peshitta.

In addition, of the early Aramaic-speaking church fathers who quoted Aramaic texts, prior to around 410 AD they quoted several different non-Peshitta Aramaic texts (including some which are different from both the Curetonian Gospels and the Syriac Sinaiticus), but never from Peshitta. Then, suddenly after approximately 410 AD, the church fathers quoted Peshitta almost exclusively.

If Peshitta were the unchanged original, then why do the church fathers quote other Aramaic NT texts prior to 410 AD? This points to the Peshitta appearing around 410 AD – which is consistent with the time period in which the Aramaic dialect of Peshitta was in use.

The final claim of AP proponents to look at is that there are supposedly clues in the text of both the Aramaic and Greek texts that point to Aramaic as being the original. Evidence for this claim mostly center around two areas: (1) there are various Aramaic phrases in the text, and (2) there are several places where translation differences between Aramaic and Greek are due to minor differences between certain Aramaic script letters, and that the Aramaic rendering makes more sense than the Greek rendering.

First, the Aramaic phrases in the text do not in any way prove that the entire NT was originally written in Aramaic. Such an argument is highly illogical, and is equivalent to saying that the use of a phrase like *et cetera* in an English language text proves that the original text was written in Latin.

Second, the translation differences relating to the variation in Aramaic script letters also does not prove Aramaic as the original language. In fact, the single-most referenced text of this type is in Matthew 19:24, Mark 10:25 and Luke 18:25 in which Jesus says that it is easier for a camel (the Greek rendering) to enter through the eye of a needle than for a rich man to enter the kingdom of God. In the Lamsa translation this is rendered as it being easier for a rope to go through the eye of a needle. The difference between “camel” and “rope” in Aramaic is supposedly one, easily confused letter, so AP proponents claim that the Aramaic must be the original and the Greek translator must have mistaken the letter. Fortunately, Bauscher does not make this mistake

However, this does not take into account the fact that the Babylonians had a saying, “It is easier for a camel to pass through the eye of a needle, than for ....” as a way of indicating that something was very difficult. Also, the Egyptians had a similar saying, “It is easier for an elephant to pass through the eye of a needle, …” If two cultures on either side of Israel, and with which the Jews had close contacts, had such sayings, why couldn’t this saying also have been used by the Jews? Given their close contact, it is reasonable to consider that the Babylonian phrase became common among the Jews and that Jesus really did say “camel” and not “rope”, and that the error in this case is in Peshitta.

In fact, of all of the “letter-swap” translation differences that I have looked at so far, all of them could just as easily  be explained by the Peshitta being a translation from Greek in which the translator had both an incomplete grasp of the Greek language as well access to earlier, fading Aramaic translations from the Greek in which some of the Aramaic letters were hard to read, and the translator picked the wrong one.

Another point that can be made relates to Acts 21:40 and Acts 26:14 in which Paul is shown to be speaking in what some translations render as Hebrew, and others as Aramaic. I looked up these texts and found that both Greek and Aramaic texts use the word for “Hebrew”. So why do some translations use “Aramaic” instead? It’s a curious question that led me to a rather interesting discovery.

In John 5:2, 19:13, 19:17 and 20:16, John uses the words Bethesda, Gabbatha, Golgotha and Rabboni, all of which are said to be “Hebrew” words in both Greek and Aramaic texts. Yet the NIV translates all four instances of the word “Hebrew” as “Aramaic”. Why? Because these really are Aramaic words, not Hebrew words (actually *rabboni* means the same thing in both Hebrew and Aramaic so it could be said to be Hebrew). So why would Aramaic words be called “Hebrew” in the original NT texts?

As far as the Greeks were concerned, any language of the Jews (Aramaic or Hebrew) was “Hebrew” and the Greeks commonly used the same word for both languages. The Hebrew and Aramaic languages, on the other hand, had different words for each other (*‘ivrit* for Hebrew and *‘aramit* for Aramaic). This means that it is more likely for the original text of John to have been in Greek, and that the Peshitta would have been translated from the Greek, keeping the “Hebrew” word.

One final nail in the Peshitta coffin relates to the name *peshitta* itself. The word means “simple” or “common”. But the question arises: simple or common *what*? In other words, simple and common are adjectives that refer to a noun. What was the noun? In the earliest Peshitta manuscripts, and in the earliest references to Peshitta by the Aramaic-speaking church fathers, they didn’t say just “peshitta”, but rather “muppaqta peshitta”. This word “muppaqta” is the noun modified by the “peshitta” adjective. So what does “muppaqta” mean? Its meaning is either “version” or “translation”. In other words, the original text of Peshitta called itself the “Easy Translation” or “Common Version”.

# Conclusion

One of Bauscher’s claims is that “Aramaic was the lingua franca of the Holy Land, Syria, Mesopotamia, Asia Minor from 700 BC to AD 700.” This is such a glaring and inaccurate misrepresentation of the language situation of the time. In fact it is so historically inaccurate that Bauscher is either grossly ignorant and the world’s worst researcher, or he is intentionally misrepresenting the facts in order to provide false support for his pet theory.

Stanley Porter provides a clear statement on the illogic of Bauscher’s claim: “I find it interesting, if not a bit perplexing, that virtually all biblical scholars will accept that the Jews adopted Aramaic, the lingua franca of the Persian empire, as their first language, with many if not most Jews of the eastern Mediterranean speaking it in the fourth century BCE. Many of these same scholars, however, will almost categorically reject the idea that the Jews adopted Greek, the lingua franca of the Graeco-Roman world, as their language, even though the social, political, cultural and, in particular, linguistic contexts were similar in so many ways, and the evidence is at least as conclusive.” (Stanley E. Porter, The Criteria for Authenticity in Historical-Jesus Research: Previous Discussion and New Proposals, Journal for the Study of the New Testament Supplement Series 191 (Sheffield, Eng.: Sheffield Academic, 2000\) 169.)

It is true that from about 700 BC to around 350 BC Aramaic was the lingua franca of the Holy Land, Syria and Mesopotamia (but not all of Asia Minor). But after the time of Alexander, the use of Greek became the predominant lingua franca even throughout modern Iran, Afghanistan and into Pakistan and northern India. Aramaic was still used, but had become fractured into numerous local backwater dialects, and was supplanted by Greek as the common language of trade, government and inter-cultural communication. This was so much the case that by the time of Christ, Greek was widely spoken in Palestine, even among the Jews.

So when I read comments and claims by Bauscher and other AP proponents regarding why the scriptures in 5th Century Edessan Syriac should be considered the originals, I am reminded of conversations I had in Poland regarding the American Revolution. For most Poles, the American Revolution is all about Tadeusz Kosciuszko and Kazimierz Pulaski. Polish people know nothing of Lafayette or von Steuben or any of the numerous other leaders who fought for American independence. To hear Poles tell it, Kosciuszko and Pulaski single-handedly won the war while everyone else sat back and watched in awe and amazement. George Washington himself is relegated to a mere side show.

Of course Kosciuszko and Pulaski played important roles in the war, but that doesn't warrant them being placed exclusively above everyone else.

In the same way, I view the Aramaic texts as an important early witness that should be consulted, but to me the evidence in support of AP – especially in reference to the entire NT – is based on bad logic, bad research or deliberate misrepresentation. All things considered, I find too much direct evidence against Aramaic Primacy for the entire NT, and therefore, reject it.

# Appendix C Miscellaneous Notes

Decapolis \- primarily Greek-speaking \- the region had previously had a low population, so the cities had been colonized by Greeks and Romans who spread their culture and Greek language. When Jesus visited Decapolis, he would have to have spoken to them in a language they were familiar with. In addition, during the Jewish Revolt of 66 to 70 AD, the Christians of Judea fled just as Jesus mentioned. Where did they go? To Pella in Decapolis. Pella was given that name because Alexander the Great was born in Pella, Macedonia. Pella was known to have been heavily Greek speaking. The Christians would have fled to a place where people spoke their language. Note the story in Mark 5:1-20 where Jesus visits the region of the "Gerasenes" \- Gerasa was one of the cities of the Decapolis, so it is more than likely that Jesus spoke Greek in this story.

Antioch \- Founded by Seleucus, the founder of the Seleucid Dynasty, Antioch was settled by Greeks and was primarily Greek-speaking. Antioch was an early center of Christianity. It was in Antioch that the term "Christian" was first used \- Christ being the Greek equivalent of Messiah. The word Christian appears in Acts 11:26, Acts 26:28 and 1 Peter 4:16. In all three cases, the Aramaic text uses the Greek-derived term *keristiyana*, not the aramaic-derived term *messiyana*.

[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hammat\_Tiberias\_Synagogue](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hammat_Tiberias_Synagogue)

* Ancient synagogue in Galilee with Greek inscriptions.

Wikipedia article on Capernaum includes mention of the synagogue uncovered during excavations \- it's from 4th century and sits on top of an older synagogue dating from the 1st century. The older (1st century) synagogue contains inscriptions in both Greek and Aramaic, indicating that both languages were in use by the synagogue's members.

* First Century Synagogue in Sardis

Excavations at Sardis Synagogue revealed 80 inscriptions in Greek, Seven in Hebrew and None in Aramaic. The Jewish community at Sardis is known to have spoken Greek, not Aramaic, further evidence disputing Bauscher’s claims.

* Theodotus Inscription

[http://www.kchanson.com/ANCDOCS/greek/theodotus.html](http://www.kchanson.com/ANCDOCS/greek/theodotus.html)

The Theodotus Inscription is a greek text written on a stone found in an archeological dig in Jerusalem. It contains an inscription in Greek about a priest who is also *archisynagogos*, or synagogue leader, and who was also the son and grandson of a synagogue leader, and who was responsible for building the synagogue where the stone was found. Due to the style of the inscription, it has been definitively dated to the time of Christ. Of note is that the greek word *archisynagogos* is the same word that appears in Mark 5:22, 35, 38; Luke 8:49; Luke 13:14; Acts 13:15; and Acts 18:8, 17\.

The earliest reference to the name Peshitta comes from the 8th Century and recognized that it’s a translation. The name *Peshitta* is actually derived from *mappaqtâ pšîṭtâ (ܡܦܩܬܐ ܦܫܝܛܬܐ)* in Syriac, which means “Simple Translation”. Here’s a dictionary entry for the word *mappaqta* which shows the meaning *translation*.

![][image1]

In *Biblical Archaeological Review*, Pieter W. Van Der Horst, points out that no less than 1,600 Jewish epitaphs \-- funerary inscriptions \-- are extant from ancient Palestine dating from 300 B.C. to 500 A.D. Speaking of all Jewish Funerary inscriptions around the world during that time period, he said, “One of the most surprising facts about these funerary inscriptions is that most of them are IN GREEK \-- approximately 70 percent; about 12 percent are in Latin; and only 18 percent are in Hebrew or Aramaic… Even in Palestine approximately TWO-THIRDS of these inscriptions are in GREEK.”

## **Josephus**

In the works of Josephus, it is interesting to note that he uses the term *syristi* to refer to Aramaic (or Syriac), and *ebraisti* to refer to Hebrew. In his writings he makes a distinction between the two languages, and from the context used, it is clear that when he refers to Hebrew, he actually does mean Hebrew, and not Aramaic.

Additionally, there are examples in his writings where he doesn’t explicitly state which language he’s referring to, but based on context, the language has to be Hebrew and not Aramaic. An example of this can be found in this excerpt from *The Jewish War*, Book 5, Chapter 6, Section 3:

"...Now, the stones that were cast \[by the Roman catapults during the siege of Jerusalem\] were of the weight of a talent, and were carried two furlongs and farther. ...As for the Jews, they at first watched the coming of the stone, for it was of a white color, and could therefore not only be perceived by the great noise it made, but could be seen also before it came by its brightness; accordingly the watchmen that sat upon the towers gave them \[the Jewish rebels\] notice when the engine was let go, and the stone came from it, and cried aloud in their own country language, "THE SON COMETH\!" so those that were in its way stood off, and threw themselves down upon the ground, by which means, and by their thus guarding themselves, the stone fell down and did them no harm. But the Romans contrived how to prevent that by blacking the stone \[an effective action by the Romans\], who then could aim at them with success, when the stone was not discerned beforehand, as it had been till then; and so they destroyed many of them at one blow."

Notice the phrase, “The Son Cometh\!”. Most translations change this to “The Stone Cometh”. However, in the Greek the exact phrase is “ὁ υἱὸς ἔρχεται”, which means “The Son Cometh”. What a strange thing to say. E.A. Knapp explains it like this:

“The phrase, “the son cometh” is clearly a play on words, and has puzzled some scholars, convinced that Aramaic was the vernacular spoken in Jerusalem at the time of the siege. In Aramaic there is no conceivable play on words that can be constructed to explain this phrase. The understanding that Hebrew was a vernacular in Judea at this time, however, makes the solution clear. The watchmen on the walls were shouting האבן בא (“ha’eben ba”) meaning “the stone is coming”; ... Thus, when said in a hurry the phrase sounded just like the phrase הבן בא (habben ba), “the son cometh” ...

(E.A. Knapp, “Did the Messiah Speak Aramaic or Hebrew, Part 4”, [http://www.torahclass.com/archived-articles/407-did-the-messiah-speak-aramaic-or-hebrew-part-4-by-eaknapp](http://www.torahclass.com/archived-articles/407-did-the-messiah-speak-aramaic-or-hebrew-part-4-by-eaknapp))

From this, it is clear that Josephus is referring to Hebrew, and not Aramaic as “their own country language”. If this is true, then his statement in *Antiquities* Book 20, Chapter 9, Section 2 (as quoted by Bauscher) could just as easily refer to Hebrew as Aramaic, since it doesn’t explicitly state which language he’s talking about.
